article.headline: Warriors put 2-point fourth-quarter behind them
article.linkText: Warriors bounce back to win at Seattle
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Golden State Warriors had something to prove. Two days after they tied an NBA record with two points in a quarter, they rebounded with a 106-97 win over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night. Jason Richardson had 22 points and Brian Cardinal added 20 for the Warriors, who scored two points in the fourth quarter of their loss to Toronto on Sunday. "I think we were making a point to come out tonight and prove that that was a fluke thing for us to score two points," Golden State coach Eric Musselman said. Mike Dunleavy contributed 10 points in 17 minutes, including two key 3-pointers late in the third quarter as Golden State opened up an eight-point lead. "I think we wanted to come out and put on a much better offensive display and we did that," he said. The Warriors won for just the sixth time in 26 road games. Clifford Robinson had 18 points, Speedy Claxton added 17 and Erick Dampier pulled down 12 rebounds for Golden State, which shot just 1-for-13 in the fourth quarter Sunday night in the overtime loss to Toronto. The Warriors had 36 points in the third period. Sunday night's defeat was so tough on the Warriors that Musselman didn't even show his team videotape of it, Richardson said. "We decided we were going to let it go," Richardson said. "We put it behind us." Rashard Lewis led the Sonics with 20 points, Ronald Murray had 19 and Vitaly Potapenko added a season-high 17 for Seattle, which lost for the fourth time in five games. Antonio Daniels filled in as the Sonics' starting point guard for Brent Barry, who has a broken ring finger on his right hand. "We play harder against each other in practice than we do against the other team," he said. "It's very frustrating." The Warriors led 88-75 with 3:35 gone in the final quarter, but the Sonics cut their deficit to 95-93 on a driving layup by Lewis with 3:36 to go. But Claxton scored on a driving layup and Richardson hit a pair of free throws after being fouled by Luke Ridnour for a 99-93 advantage with two minutes remaining. Golden State opened the second half with a 14-2 run and got a pair of 3-pointers from Dunleavy in the final minute of the third quarter to go in front 79-71. The Sonics didn't score a basket in the second half until Dampier was called for goaltending on a shot by Potapenko with 4:15 gone. Ray Allen suffered a sprained left shoulder Friday night in Phoenix and said it was still bothering him. He scored 15 points on 6-for-19 shooting in 42 minutes. "I don't have any strength on the left side of my shoulder and it causes me to rotate in awkward positions to avoid getting hit," he said. "I had some good shots tonight, but I didn't have any comfort with it because it just seemed like every time I went up, I was grimacing when I was shooting." Dunleavy returned to the Warriors' lineup after missing four games, entering the game with 20 seconds left in the opening quarter. In 17 minutes, he scored 10 points. It was his first action since spraining his left ankle Jan. 30 against Chicago.

Game notes
McMillan doesn't sound as if he expects his team's front office to make any trades before the Feb. 19 NBA trading deadline. "You don't make a move just to patch up things," McMillan said. "It's a long-term plan here. It's a young team. We knew we would have some tough times. If you push the panic button, it could cost you. If nothing happens, it means it doesn't make sense for the Sonics." ... The four games missed by Dunleavy were the first of his career. He was the third player drafted in 2002.
